Honestly seeing people do this really gets me down. Like am I really making a difference at all 😫!! I really try to understand where people are coming from with many things they do as parents but I really can’t wrap my head around my child is crying and upset. Now I will go pick up my phone and record them crying and ask them to tell the camera about it? Maybe laugh? 

It’s weirder to me that people do this to show other moms that their children are “bad” or them struggling. We all get it that children have tantrums. I just don’t know why anyone thinks that’s a good idea. 

Doing that should make you think of a time you were really vulnerable and sad. Even if it was not a huge deal. You’re crying. Then imagine someone comes up and records you and laughs in your face? You probably wouldn’t like that person very much. The sad part is the child doesn’t realize that this isn’t normal but they do learn that their experience is invalid and they can’t trust you to be there for them.  Just please don’t do it. It’s not funny. It’s not cute. It’s damaging. Put the phone down and connect in real life.

We all do this right? Lol 😆 

I love this audio with Avan. It’s a year old when life was quite different for the both of us. ♥️ a year can change so much.

2022 taught me more than any other year in life so far… it especially taught me the value of time and giving your time to things you value. 

In this picture Isla is 1 week old and cuddling skin to skin. Something we did everyday for the first few months until she wouldn’t nap on me anymore. Those moments are forever a part of me. 

I really slowed down this year and used my time very intentionally. I’ve been very present with who or what I’m with. 

2022 also completely transformed what matters to me. I’ve never been this clear. I’ve never understood the meaning of my life this well. I can’t believe all that has happened in a year. 

I don’t want to give energy or space to people or things I don’t align with. I’m not forcing anything. It flows or it goes. I think we often over complicate things because the mind gets so fixated on what people think or what others are doing. I’ve learned focusing more on you is where happiness is… 

… it’s dancing in the living room with your spouse, belly laughing on the floor with your toddler, watching your baby eat food, running around in the yard, working with clients who inspire you, being with family and friends, the list goes on and on. But they’re all “small” unless we are present. 

My hope for your 2023 is that you are present with your life and the people in it 🎁

I’m excited to create more this next year and be of service. Happy New Year friends 🎊
My hope for you this year is that you create a life that feels worthy to you not that looks worthy to others ❤️

When people yell it’s typically because they do not have the emotional intelligence or awareness to communicate calmly. For a child who is trying to understand the world and who they are being yelled at makes them feel like they’re bad. They don’t yet understand that people who yell don’t have these life skills. Then they take it on and typically pass it on to their child because it’s a learned behavior. If you struggle with this, know that you can work through it. You can learn to manage your emotions. You can break the cycle ♥️ it’s not your fault but it is your responsibility to work through.

Gentle parenting isn’t a researched or studied parenting style but based on what I have been seeing is that a lot of people grew up in authoritarian or neglectful homes and they swung to permissive parenting. We just call it gentle parenting now and have grouped a few things in there so I want to outline the differences.

While permissive parenting can feel really good to feel like you’re giving your child everything in unlimited amount. Not saying no. No rules and so on. Outside of giving love freely and openly it’s really harmful to a child’s growth. Children have been proven to thrive best with clear boundaries that are reasonable, they’re explained and held in homes with love and kindness. This gives them a sense of safety and to not have a need to be in fight or flight mode which is what a lack of boundaries can cause. They feel out of control because they are new here and do not know what’s what. It’s actually a lot to expect of a child and we are their guides for a short time. 

This is my first step in spreading more awareness and information on this topic I feel a burning passion for because when I am looking around I fear people (with great intentions) are swinging from one extreme to another. The best thing you can do when parenting is work on healing your trauma so you can set boundaries and you can parent lovingly. It is love to help your child develop into a responsible and respectful adult! 

What’s your parenting style? What did you grow up with?

I grew up with authoritarian parents and parent as an authoritative parent. Lots of love and kindness but also reasonable expectations. ❤️🤗
